<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S2.SS1.p9">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">As mentioned earlier, the framework described here is ge=
neral enough
to accommodate classical, deterministic systems. For example, a Newtonian
system based on deterministic, second-order equations of motion is
equivalent to a stochastic process whose nomological content consists
of only second-order conditional probabilities, with values equal
to <math alttext=3D"1" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S2.SS1.p=
9.m1"><semantics><mn>1</mn><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">1</an=
notation><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">1</annotation></se=
mantics></math> or <math alttext=3D"0" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline=
" id=3D"S2.SS1.p9.m2"><mn>0</mn></math> (or, more properly delta functions)=
, and with times
<math alttext=3D"t,t_{1},t_{2}" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D=
"S2.SS1.p9.m3"><semantics><mrow><mi>t</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</=
mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><annotation enc=
oding=3D"application/x-tex">t,t_{1},t_{2}</annotation><annotation encoding=
=3D"application/x-llamapun">italic_t , italic_t start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_P=
OSTSUBSCRIPT , italic_t start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT</annotation=
></semantics></math> separated by vanishingly small durations.</p><button c=
lass=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">Report issue for preceding=
 element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S2.SS1.p10">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">A stochastic process is said to be <em class=3D"ltx_emph=
 ltx_font_italic">Markovian</em> if all its second-
and higher-order transition probabilities <math alttext=3D"p\mathopen{}\mat=
hclose{{\left(i,t|j_{1},t_{1};j_{2},t_{2},\dots}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_math=
_unparsed" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S2.SS1.p10.m1"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</=
mi><mrow><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>i</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>t</mi><mo fence=
