<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S2.SS2.p2">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">Importantly, notice that the law of total probability (<=
a class=3D"ltx_ref" href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2507.21192v1#S2.E19" tit=
le=3D"In 2.2 Indivisible Stochastic Processes =E2=80=A3 2 Stochastic Proces=
ses =E2=80=A3 Quantum Systems as Indivisible Stochastic Processes"><span cl=
ass=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">19</span></a>)
is <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">linear</em>, in the sense that it=
 establishes a linear relationship
between the system=E2=80=99s standalone probabilities at <math alttext=3D"t=
_{0}" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S2.SS2.p2.m1"><semantics>=
<msub><mi>t</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex"=
>t_{0}</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">italic_t=
 start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 0 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT</annotation></semantics></math> an=
d the
system=E2=80=99s standalone probabilities at <math alttext=3D"t" class=3D"l=
tx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S2.SS2.p2.m2"><semantics><mi>t</mi><annot=
ation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">t</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"=
application/x-llamapun">italic_t</annotation></semantics></math>. This line=
arity will turn
out to underwrite the linearity of time evolution for closed quantum
systems.</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">Repor=
t issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S2.SS2.p3">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">Note that no assumption is made here that the transition=
 probabilities
<math alttext=3D"p\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(i,t|j,t_{0}}}\right)" class=
=3D"ltx_math_unparsed" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S2.SS2.p3.m1"><semantics><m=
