real-valued choices of <math alttext=3D"t_{0}" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=
=3D"inline" id=3D"S2.SS2.p3.m2"><semantics><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>0</mn></msub=
><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">t_{0}</annotation><annotation e=
ncoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">italic_t start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 0 end_POSTS=
UBSCRIPT</annotation></semantics></math>. Allowed conditioning times <math =
alttext=3D"t_{0}" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S2.SS2.p3.m3"=
><semantics><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><annotation encoding=3D"applic=
ation/x-tex">t_{0}</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-llamap=
un">italic_t start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 0 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT</annotation></semantic=
s></math>
are called <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">division events</em> for =
the given system, and, without
any real loss of generality, are assumed to include an =E2=80=98initial=E2=
=80=99
time <math alttext=3D"0" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S2.SS2=
.p3.m4"><mn>0</mn></math>.</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"dis=
play: none;">Report issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S2.SS2.p4">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">Division events are not global properties of the whole u=
niverse, but
are system-centric, just like various other kinds of spontaneous time-trans=
lation-breaking
in physics. In practice, a system may have multiple exact division
events, or they may be generated to an extremely good approximation
through interactions with other systems, after marginalizing over
those other systems (Barandes 2025).</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" st=
yle=3D"display: none;">Report issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S2.SS2.p5">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">The target time <math alttext=3D"t" class=3D"ltx_Math" d=
isplay=3D"inline" id=3D"S2.SS2.p5.m1"><semantics><mi>t</mi><annotation enco=
ding=3D"application/x-tex">t</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"applicatio=
n/x-llamapun">italic_t</annotation></semantics></math>, by contrast, can be=
 treated as a free variable.
In particular, no assumption is made that <math alttext=3D"t&gt;t_{0}" clas=
s=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S2.SS2.p5.m2"><semantics><mrow><mi>=
t</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow><annotation enco=
ding=3D"application/x-tex">t&gt;t_{0}</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"a=
pplication/x-llamapun">italic_t &gt; italic_t start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 0 end_POS=
TSUBSCRIPT</annotation></semantics></math>. One can choose
<math alttext=3D"t&lt;t_{0}" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S2=
.SS2.p5.m3"><semantics><mrow><mi>t</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>0</=
mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">t&lt;t_{0}</ann=
