<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S3.SS4.p5">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">In keeping with Bell=E2=80=99s terminology, random varia=
bles will now be called
<em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">be-ables</em>, or <em class=3D"ltx_e=
mph ltx_font_italic">beables</em> (Bell 1973, 1976).
When the system is any given configuration <math alttext=3D"i" class=3D"ltx=
_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.SS4.p5.m1"><semantics><mi>i</mi><annotat=
ion encoding=3D"application/x-tex">i</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"ap=
plication/x-llamapun">italic_i</annotation></semantics></math>, each beable=
 <math alttext=3D"A\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_ma=
th_unparsed" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.SS4.p5.m2"><semantics><mrow><mi>A<=
/mi><mrow><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow=
><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">A\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t=
}}\right)</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">itali=
c_A start_OPEN end_OPEN start_CLOSE ( italic_t end_CLOSE )</annotation></se=
mantics></math>
has a definite, underlying value <math alttext=3D"a\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\=
left(i,t}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_math_unparsed" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.=
SS4.p5.m3"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi><mrow><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>i<=
/mi><mo>,</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=
=3D"application/x-tex">a\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(i,t}}\right)</annotati=
on><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">italic_a start_OPEN end_=
OPEN start_CLOSE ( italic_i , italic_t end_CLOSE )</annotation></semantics>=
</math>. Bell intended
to distinguish beables from mere observables, which, by the Kochen-Specker
theorem (Bell 1966; Kochen, Specker 1967),
cannot all be beables.</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display=
: none;">Report issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S3.SS4.p6">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">Observables that are not beables are non-diagonal self-a=
djoint operators
that correspond to emergent patterns that show up when systems interact
with measuring devices, and will be called <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_i=
talic">emergeables</em> (Barandes 2025).
The idea of emergeables goes back to Bohr (Bohr 1935, Bell 1971),
and also figures prominently in Bohmian mechanics (Bell 1982, Daumer
et al. 1996).
A system=E2=80=99s beables and its emergeables collectively comprise the sy=
stem=E2=80=99s
overall non-commutative algebra of observables. When a measuring device
is properly modeled as one additional part of a larger stochastic
process, along the lines presented in the present paper, one can show
that at the end of the measurement process, the measuring device will
end up in one of its possible measurement-outcome configurations with
a stochastic probability that coincides with the standard Born rule,
whether the measuring device has been tuned to measure a beable or
an emergeable (Barandes 2025).</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D=
"display: none;">Report issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
