<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S3.SS5.p5">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">In general, an <math alttext=3D"N\times N" class=3D"ltx_=
Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.SS5.p5.m1"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi><mo=
 lspace=3D"0.222em" rspace=3D"0.222em">=C3=97</mo><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotat=
ion encoding=3D"application/x-tex">N\times N</annotation><annotation encodi=
ng=3D"application/x-llamapun">italic_N =C3=97 italic_N</annotation></semant=
ics></math> matrix is called <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">unistoc=
hastic</em>
if its individual entries are expressible as the modulus-squares of
the corresponding entries of an <math alttext=3D"N\times N" class=3D"ltx_Ma=
th" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.SS5.p5.m2"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi><mo l=
space=3D"0.222em" rspace=3D"0.222em">=C3=97</mo><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotatio=
n encoding=3D"application/x-tex">N\times N</annotation><annotation encoding=
=3D"application/x-llamapun">italic_N =C3=97 italic_N</annotation></semantic=
s></math> unitary matrix. It follows
that (<a class=3D"ltx_ref" href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2507.21192v1#S3.E=
64" title=3D"In 3.5 Kraus Decompositions and Unitary Time Evolution =E2=80=
=A3 3 Review of the Stochastic-Quantum Correspondence =E2=80=A3 Quantum Sys=
tems as Indivisible Stochastic Processes"><span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_t=
ag">64</span></a>) is just
the statement that the system=E2=80=99s transition matrix <math alttext=3D"=
\Gamma\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t\leftarrow 0}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_mat=
h_unparsed" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.SS5.p5.m3"><semantics><mrow><mi mat=
hvariant=3D"normal">=CE=93</mi><mrow><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo=
 stretchy=3D"false">=E2=86=90</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow>=
<annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\Gamma\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\le=
ft(t\leftarrow 0}}\right)</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"application/x=
-llamapun">roman_=CE=93 start_OPEN end_OPEN start_CLOSE ( italic_t =E2=86=
=90 0 end_CLOSE )</annotation></semantics></math>
can be taken to be unistochastic, and will therefore be said to describe
a <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">unistochastic process</em>.</p><bu=
tton class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">Report issue for pre=
ceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S3.SS5.p6">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">The preceding analysis implies that an indivisible stoch=
astic process
can be viewed either as a unistochastic process itself, or (if a nontrivial
dilation was required) as a <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">subsyste=
m</em> of a unistochastic process.
This statement is called the <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">stochas=
tic-quantum theorem</em> (Barandes 2023).</p><button class=3D"sr-only butto=
n" style=3D"display: none;">Report issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S3.SS5.p7">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">Note that a unitary time-evolution operator <math alttex=
t=3D"U\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t\leftarrow 0}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_mat=
h_unparsed" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.SS5.p7.m1"><semantics><mrow><mi>U</=
mi><mrow><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=3D"false">=E2=86=
=90</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"ap=
plication/x-tex">U\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t\leftarrow 0}}\right)</anno=
tation><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">italic_U start_OPEN =
end_OPEN start_CLOSE ( italic_t =E2=86=90 0 end_CLOSE )</annotation></seman=
tics></math>
will not generically remain unitary under arbitrary Schur-Hadamard
gauge transformations (<a class=3D"ltx_ref" href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/=
2507.21192v1#S3.E30" title=3D"In 3.2 Schur-Hadamard Gauge Transformations =
=E2=80=A3 3 Review of the Stochastic-Quantum Correspondence =E2=80=A3 Quant=
um Systems as Indivisible Stochastic Processes"><span class=3D"ltx_text ltx=
_ref_tag">30</span></a>).
Hence, writing a unistochastic transition matrix <math alttext=3D"\Gamma\ma=
thopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t\leftarrow 0}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_math_unparse=
