<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S3.SS6.p2">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">If the unitary matrix <math alttext=3D"V\mathopen{}\math=
close{{\left(t}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_math_unparsed" display=3D"inline" id=
=3D"S3.SS6.p2.m1"><semantics><mrow><mi>V</mi><mrow><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo=
><mi>t</mi></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"applicati=
on/x-tex">V\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t}}\right)</annotation><annotation =
encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">italic_V start_OPEN end_OPEN start_CLOS=
E ( italic_t end_CLOSE )</annotation></semantics></math> is taken to be tim=
e-<em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">independent</em>,
then the Foldy-Wouthuysen gauge transformation (<a class=3D"ltx_ref" href=
=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2507.21192v1#S3.E74" title=3D"In 3.6 Foldy-Wouth=
uysen Gauge Transformations =E2=80=A3 3 Review of the Stochastic-Quantum Co=
rrespondence =E2=80=A3 Quantum Systems as Indivisible Stochastic Processes"=
><span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">74</span></a>)
is merely a simple change of orthonormal basis. However, if <math alttext=
=3D"V\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_math_unparsed" d=
isplay=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.SS6.p2.m2"><semantics><mrow><mi>V</mi><mrow><mi>=
</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><annotation e=
ncoding=3D"application/x-tex">V\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t}}\right)</ann=
otation><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">italic_V start_OPEN=
 end_OPEN start_CLOSE ( italic_t end_CLOSE )</annotation></semantics></math=
>
depends nontrivially on time, and if one regards the system=E2=80=99s Hilbe=
rt
space at each moment in time as a fiber over a one-dimensional base
manifold parameterized by the time coordinate <math alttext=3D"t" class=3D"=
ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.SS6.p2.m3"><semantics><mi>t</mi><anno=
tation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">t</annotation><annotation encoding=3D=
"application/x-llamapun">italic_t</annotation></semantics></math>, then <ma=
th alttext=3D"V\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_math_u=
nparsed" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.SS6.p2.m4"><semantics><mrow><mi>V</mi>=
<mrow><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><an=
notation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">V\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t}}\r=
ight)</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">italic_V =
start_OPEN end_OPEN start_CLOSE ( italic_t end_CLOSE )</annotation></semant=
ics></math>
represents a local-in-time, unitary transformation of each individual
Hilbert-space fiber. In particular, any given time-dependent state
vector <math alttext=3D"\Psi\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t}}\right)" class=
=3D"ltx_math_unparsed" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.SS6.p2.m5"><semantics><m=
row><mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=CE=A8</mi><mrow><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><m=
i>t</mi></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/=
x-tex">\Psi\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t}}\right)</annotation><annotation =
encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">roman_=CE=A8 start_OPEN end_OPEN start_=
CLOSE ( italic_t end_CLOSE )</annotation></semantics></math>, regarded as a=
 trajectory through the
system=E2=80=99s Hilbert space, can be mapped to any other trajectory by a
suitable choice of time-dependent unitary matrix <math alttext=3D"V\mathope=
n{}\mathclose{{\left(t}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_math_unparsed" display=3D"inl=
ine" id=3D"S3.SS6.p2.m6"><semantics><mrow><mi>V</mi><mrow><mi></mi><mrow><m=
o>(</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"ap=
plication/x-tex">V\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t}}\right)</annotation><anno=
tation encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">italic_V start_OPEN end_OPEN sta=
rt_CLOSE ( italic_t end_CLOSE )</annotation></semantics></math>,
so trajectories in the Hilbert space do not describe gauge-invariant
facts.</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">Report =
issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S3.SS6.p3">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">These formulas make manifest that the Hilbert-space form=
ulation of
an indivisible stochastic process is ultimately a collection of gauge-depen=
dent
quantities, or gauge variables. In any physical theory, one does not
typically try to assign gauge variables an ontological meaning. The
familiar ingredients of the Hilbert-space formulation are highly gauge-depe=
ndent
according to both kinds of gauge transformations described in the
present paper=E2=80=94Schur-Hadamard gauge transformations (<a class=3D"ltx=
_ref" href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2507.21192v1#S3.E29" title=3D"In 3.2 S=
chur-Hadamard Gauge Transformations =E2=80=A3 3 Review of the Stochastic-Qu=
antum Correspondence =E2=80=A3 Quantum Systems as Indivisible Stochastic Pr=
ocesses"><span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">29</span></a>)
and Foldy-Wouthuysen gauge transformations (<a class=3D"ltx_ref" href=3D"ht=
tps://arxiv.org/html/2507.21192v1#S3.E74" title=3D"In 3.6 Foldy-Wouthuysen =
Gauge Transformations =E2=80=A3 3 Review of the Stochastic-Quantum Correspo=
ndence =E2=80=A3 Quantum Systems as Indivisible Stochastic Processes"><span=
 class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">74</span></a>).
Hence, although a Hilbert-space formulation may be extremely useful
for constructing stochastic dynamics or for carrying out calculations,
one might rightly be skeptical about trying to assign direct physical
meanings to its mathematical ingredients, or suspicious of any interpretati=
on
of quantum theory based on reifying, say, wave functions or density
matrices as parts of the ontological furniture of reality.</p><button class=
=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">Report issue for preceding ele=
