<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S4.SS1.p9">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">As a potentially new result, the condition (<a class=3D"=
ltx_ref" href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2507.21192v1#S4.E87" title=3D"In 4.=
1 Dynamical Symmetries =E2=80=A3 4 Further Implications =E2=80=A3 Quantum S=
ystems as Indivisible Stochastic Processes"><span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref=
_tag">87</span></a>)
may also open up the possibility of dynamical symmetries that are
distinct from the unitary and anti-unitary cases. This possibility
does not contradict Wigner=E2=80=99s theorem (Wigner 1931),
because the discussion at this point is pitched at the level of an
<em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">entire system</em>, which may explic=
itly include measuring devices
as subsystems. As explained in other work (Barandes 2025),
if one suitably models an entire system that includes a measuring
device as an overall unistochastic process, then the measuring device
will end up in one of its possible measurement-outcome configurations
with the appropriate Born-rule probability for whatever observable
is measured=E2=80=94whether a beable (represented by a self-adjoint
matrix that is diagonal in the configuration basis) or an emergeable
(represented by a non-diagonal self-adjoint matrix). Relative phases
in this overall unistochastic process are immaterial gauge variables.</p><b=
utton class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">Report issue for pr=
eceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S4.SS1.p10">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">However, for Wigner=E2=80=99s theorem, as with the tradi=
tional textbook formulation
of the Dirac-von Neumann axioms, one assumes that an <em class=3D"ltx_emph =
ltx_font_italic">implicit</em>
measuring device is left out of the Hilbert-space formalism, and one
can appeal to the Born rule and the collapse rule as bare posits.
In particular, the implicit measuring device does not participate
in the invertible transformation in question, and one needs to be
mindful of relative phases in the quantum system that the measuring
device is investigating. Because beables and emergeables in the quantum
system appear on an essentially similar footing as far as the implicit
measuring device is concerned, one therefore needs to specialize the
dynamical symmetries (<a class=3D"ltx_ref" href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2=
507.21192v1#S4.E87" title=3D"In 4.1 Dynamical Symmetries =E2=80=A3 4 Furthe=
r Implications =E2=80=A3 Quantum Systems as Indivisible Stochastic Processe=
s"><span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">87</span></a>)
to a smaller class of transformations, which will be called <em class=3D"lt=
x_emph ltx_font_italic">Wigner symmetries</em>.</p><button class=3D"sr-only=
 button" style=3D"display: none;">Report issue for preceding element</butto=
n>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S4.SS1.p11">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">After carrying out a Wigner symmetry, any emergeables ex=
hibited by
the quantum system should still be available to measuring devices.
Each emergeable, being represented by a self-adjoint operator, corresponds
to a PVM of its own, so if <math alttext=3D"P_{\alpha}^{\prime}" class=3D"l=
tx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS1.p11.m1"><semantics><msubsup><mi>P<=
